metadata.name: RULES (for Elementary Cellular Automata) #412
metadata.description:
An important element of generative art is emergence. The most famous algorithm for this is probably Cellular Automata (CA).

However, numerous generative artists have created works using CA, which has lost its visual freshness and is like chewing gum that has lost its taste.

Although it is such a classic algorithm, adding my own little ideas to it and finding a new "flavor" is the reason why I code.

Here, the subject is 1D Elementary Cellular Automata, the simplest of all cellular automata. 1D Elementary Cellular Automata has 256 different rules, which change the shapes produced. This work aims to create more complex shapes by randomly selecting some of those rules and placing multiple of them on the screen.

The on/off of the CA cell is often likened to the behavior of living creatures.As of 2022, in the country where I live, prices are rising, wages are not increasing, and COVID-19 has not yet ended. I created this work with the image of people at the mercy of these various rules.

---

Screen click: Change rules
S key: Save png
L key: Show/hide grid

metadata.name: Curlida #145
metadata.description:
Fully generative art. Each token is 100% unique.

Traits:
- 28 color palettes;
- 5 "stylers" - cells filling style;
- 3 "ratio" - aspect ratio.

Press 's' to save png.

High-level description of the algorithm:
Frame is separated into flows using several different Perlin noise generators. 
Frame cells are filled with curves. Each curve is drawn in the direction plotted by noise generator.
Each value returned by the generator at (x, y) is mapped to color from a predefined range.


Made with p5js, math and love by @ivposure

metadata.name: Solace #57
metadata.description:
Solace is an algorithm that generates artworks of sand dunes. It draws hundreds of thousands of tiny points according to a probability distribution calculated from the positions of the dunes.

The logic to divide the dunes into light and dark sides is simple, but produces some interesting chaotic behaviour. These are details that weren't hard-coded but emerge organically, such as the patterns on the spines of the dunes or the stripes around their bases.

Please note that the algorithm can take some time to run, especially when the number of dunes is high.

Created by lunarean.

metadata.name: Paleterum #172
metadata.description:
Notes: GPU intensive. May not render on some mobile devices. Renders fastest with Chrome.

Controls:
Press “s” to save .png
Press 1-4 to change resolution:
1 - 1000px * 1410px
2 - 2000px * 2820px 
3 - 3000px * 4230px
4 - 4000px * 5640px 

Default resolution is 1000px * 1410px. It is recommended to explore in 2000px * 2820px or above.

Paleterum (latin “plate”, “board”) — a flat surface that is used by artists to hold and mix colors.
This artwork is an attempt to simulate the look of watercolor on paper. Inspired by childhood memories that passed through the watercolor sketches of my mother, who was an artist, the piece reflects my admiration for her work and her influence on my own artistic endeavors. 
Intricate forms contrast with the strict forms of cells. All these are echoes from childhood - watercolor lines of a child not bothered by a special artistic idea but trying at least to a fraction of mastering the fine arts and cubes reminiscent of ones which children use to build towers.
Overall, the piece is a tribute to the joy and creativity of childhood, and to the power of artistic inspiration that can be passed down from one generation to the next.

Made with p5js and a few GLSL shaders.

metadata.description: "A LITTLE SPLASH" is a generative piece of software coded using p5js by a biological intelligence.

metadata.name: Utopian Skyline #79
metadata.description:
Continuing the exploration of linear composition in the previous work, this work shows the utopian urban structure in an abstract form by using diagonal and non-uniform lines. To make this artwork more scattered and visually dynamic, just like musical notes that have to be interrupted somewhere, the lines are scattered and discontinuous using an animation algorithm. To see the artwork in detail, open it in high quality and zoom in. Various densities and color palettes have been used.

-----------

- Add &density=2 to 12 to the live view URL to render the image at higher resolution.

- Press ’s’ on the live mode to save the artwork.

Made with p5js.

metadata.name: Ridge Blur #340
metadata.description:
This work is the second in the ridge series. While using the same base algorithm this work is about exploring landscapes using a much more dark and desolate imagery.

It was designed to be experienced in fullscreen in live mode.
Press "s" to save a screenshot.

Dutch auction (14/11/8), updating every 5min.

Original artwork by William Watkins · Lyon, 2022

metadata.name: Ōmukade #282
metadata.description:
Dance of many legs. Moving fast knows that nothing can forever last. For if it stops, it meets its end, no pause allowed.

Consume and avoid obstacles. Don't hit the wall, don't hit yourself.

How to play:
- WASD/Arrow keys: Move
- Double click/tap: show/hide touch control
- P: Screenshot

metadata.name: First Dance #263
metadata.description:
As imperfect and exciting as your first dance.

This project is meant to be a casual/fun minting experience to show appreciation to those that supported any of my projects in 2022. Thank you all.

Each output is generated from code written in p5js.

Created by Eric Davidson. 2023.
